00:03:57.460 --> 00:04:06.860
So Satish, as we wait for questions to come in from everybody here, I'd love to hear what

00:04:07.699 --> 00:04:11.460
is something that, this is a question we tend to ask a lot of people, what is something

00:04:11.460 --> 00:04:15.860
that you're excited about in the year ahead for your team?

00:04:15.860 --> 00:04:22.579
Yeah, as I indicated earlier, we have the statistical program and compute engine, what

00:04:22.579 --> 00:04:28.779
is called SPACE inside Janssen to help our scientists.

00:04:28.779 --> 00:04:33.899
One of the things that we are looking forward is to add capabilities to this platform because

00:04:34.339 --> 00:04:42.700
as the adoption grows, as folks slowly start seeing the power of R and the open source

00:04:42.700 --> 00:04:49.140
community support that has really been the big reason for us to adopt R because there

00:04:49.140 --> 00:04:53.540
is always learn from others experience as well.

00:04:53.540 --> 00:05:01.179
So we are trying to see how we can grow the R use case and adopt it, number one, and at

00:05:01.179 --> 00:05:06.500
the same time, enable other tools and technologies that our users are asking.

00:05:06.500 --> 00:05:12.940
For example, we just introduced the, for some of the folks who were wanting to leverage

00:05:12.940 --> 00:05:16.500
Python, we just added the capability as well.

00:05:16.500 --> 00:05:21.899
One of the things that I'm proud of is, this is all in a validated environment.

00:05:21.899 --> 00:05:26.700
There are some challenges that come along with it and we are partnering with a Taurus

00:05:26.700 --> 00:05:30.940
team to help us with the validation aspect of it.

00:05:30.980 --> 00:05:35.459
Any GXP platform, as folks might know, there are two things in there.

00:05:35.459 --> 00:05:42.500
One is a formal verification that somebody traditional in IT like myself would be responsible

00:05:42.500 --> 00:05:47.339
for it because that's, it's crucial and we have to build a platform like this.

00:05:47.339 --> 00:05:53.420
It's absolutely essential that we have to do a repeated install of this just to prove

00:05:53.420 --> 00:06:01.019
that what we installed today is the same thing that we can install tomorrow because

00:06:01.019 --> 00:06:03.579
that will increase the user confidence.

00:06:03.579 --> 00:06:06.839
The other aspect of it is the validation.

00:06:06.839 --> 00:06:13.619
What we have installed, will, are the users comfortable with the confidence that what

00:06:13.619 --> 00:06:16.980
they run today, they're going to get the same results.

00:06:16.980 --> 00:06:23.299
That is the formal verification slash validation process that we are partnering with Taurus

00:06:23.299 --> 00:06:28.459
to build some of the capabilities to support us in that effort.

00:06:28.459 --> 00:06:33.420
As we continue to add platforms, of course, you know, we have to keep up with technology.

00:06:33.420 --> 00:06:38.059
We have to keep up with what is out there and some of the things that I'm looking forward

00:06:38.059 --> 00:06:43.059
is, you know, traditionally, if I have to wear a development hat at this time, some

00:06:43.059 --> 00:06:46.380
of the platforms that we are running are on RHEL 7.

00:06:46.380 --> 00:06:51.380
As we think about, you know, RHEL 7 being going, you know, rather sun setting, what

00:06:51.380 --> 00:06:55.019
is it that we need to do to build on RHEL 8 platforms?

00:06:55.019 --> 00:06:58.140
What are the tools that are available?

00:06:58.140 --> 00:07:03.380
So that is what is, I'm looking forward from that perspective because that's an immediate

00:07:03.380 --> 00:07:05.739
challenge as folks might know.

00:07:05.739 --> 00:07:12.540
We are, RHEL 7 is going out of support by end of this year with an additional six months

00:07:12.540 --> 00:07:18.959
of extended support formally by Red Hat, but beyond that, we have to think about something.

00:07:18.959 --> 00:07:24.040
This is a little bit more tactical in nature, but we have to go through the entire process

00:07:24.040 --> 00:07:26.279
of migrating to a new platform.

00:07:26.279 --> 00:07:35.399
Thank you, Satish, and I see Eric commenting on the migrations as well.

00:07:35.399 --> 00:07:41.119
I was just going to ask, so for someone like myself who isn't in the pharma industry and

00:07:41.119 --> 00:07:48.920
is not familiar with like more of the admin side of things, what does like having a validated

00:07:48.920 --> 00:07:52.040
environment really mean?

00:07:52.040 --> 00:07:53.040
Good question.

00:07:53.040 --> 00:08:01.160
Validated environment to me is, you know, say for example, pharma and finance is another

00:08:01.160 --> 00:08:04.500
example of regulated industries, correct?

00:08:04.500 --> 00:08:10.959
What it means is, you know, anytime a health reporting agency comes and asks for proof,

00:08:10.959 --> 00:08:17.519
we have to be comfortable in saying that what we ran a couple of days ago, months ago, weeks

00:08:17.519 --> 00:08:24.519
ago, or years ago, we need to be in a position to replicate that entire environment as is.

00:08:24.519 --> 00:08:31.640
So, this goes through a formal validation slash verification process, and this in traditional

00:08:31.640 --> 00:08:34.840
parlance is known as a GXP platform.

00:08:34.840 --> 00:08:41.719
GXP is good, X will stand for clinical practice, manufacturing practice, lab practice.

00:08:42.119 --> 00:08:48.039
So, the verification validated environment is often referred to as a GXP environment.

00:08:48.039 --> 00:08:53.479
So, it is to build confidence for the end users that we serve in pharma.

00:08:53.479 --> 00:08:59.479
It is for folks who want to help deliver patient care, which is crucial.

00:08:59.479 --> 00:09:05.719
This is where the validated environment or this is what the validated environment is, Rachel.

00:09:05.719 --> 00:09:09.719
Thank you, that's really helpful.

00:09:09.880 --> 00:09:15.479
I did see there are a few anonymous questions starting to come in, so I want to go ask one

00:09:15.479 --> 00:09:21.159
over there, but somebody had asked, when talking about R, we hear a lot from a data science

00:09:21.159 --> 00:09:28.679
or engineering perspective, what do you think the differences in thought are from an IT perspective?

00:09:29.960 --> 00:09:32.280
From an IT perspective, yeah, good question.

00:09:33.159 --> 00:09:40.119
So, the one advantage that we have with R is, as I mentioned earlier, the power of open

00:09:40.119 --> 00:09:44.840
source where folks are contributing to the R ecosystem as such.

00:09:44.840 --> 00:09:49.000
So, there are more and more folks who are contributing to it.

00:09:49.000 --> 00:09:53.960
It could be, you know, at the end of the day, it's a traditional R package that gets developed.

00:09:54.760 --> 00:10:01.960
And often what we are seeing is, from an IT perspective, there are some challenges in

00:10:01.960 --> 00:10:04.599
reproducing this platform as is.

00:10:04.599 --> 00:10:09.559
Sometimes, you know, the frustration that our users have is, hey, it worked yesterday.

00:10:10.359 --> 00:10:14.280
How, you know, why am I, you know, I tried the exact same thing today.

00:10:14.280 --> 00:10:16.599
Why am I having issues with that?

00:10:16.599 --> 00:10:17.960
And there are various reasons.

00:10:18.200 --> 00:10:25.159
Because, you know, we might be using version one of one particular package, but underneath

00:10:25.159 --> 00:10:29.880
that, it will go and pull certain dependencies, which could be a function of time.

00:10:30.520 --> 00:10:38.119
But there are tools that are available today to help us with that approach.

00:10:38.119 --> 00:10:42.039
In other words, you know, there is an R package that folks are familiar with,

00:10:42.039 --> 00:10:45.719
RENB as an example, where you can lock the versions.

00:10:45.719 --> 00:10:51.719
We are also using Deposit Package Manager as well to help us with snapshotting capabilities.

00:10:52.280 --> 00:10:59.719
And this is where, you know, IT can step in, implement these tools so that, you know, users

00:10:59.719 --> 00:11:05.479
can be confident that what they did today, they should be able to reproduce the same

00:11:05.479 --> 00:11:07.320
environment tomorrow as well.

00:11:09.719 --> 00:11:15.320
So Bill had asked, do you have SAS and R running on the same validated server?

00:11:15.320 --> 00:11:17.400
Is that server in the cloud?

00:11:17.400 --> 00:11:20.280
And is that managed by an external service provider?

00:11:22.520 --> 00:11:25.400
Maybe I'll try and break this up into multiple questions.

00:11:25.400 --> 00:11:30.200
But Bill also asked, are you having a hard time finding a cloud hosting service provider?

00:11:32.280 --> 00:11:33.479
Who is doing that for you today?

00:11:34.679 --> 00:11:35.479
Fair question.

00:11:37.000 --> 00:11:42.520
One, we have completely adopted a cloud, at least inside Janssen.

00:11:42.520 --> 00:11:46.119
Most of what we do, it is with the cloud provider.

00:11:46.119 --> 00:11:49.239
And we have a huge investment with AWS.

00:11:49.239 --> 00:11:54.440
We are partnering with AWS as and when we would want new capabilities.

00:11:54.440 --> 00:12:01.799
We do work with them and see where they could help us implement certain services that we would need.

00:12:02.520 --> 00:12:09.000
Now, AWS might be ready, but then our technology services team would want to ensure,

00:12:09.000 --> 00:12:13.719
because it's in the cloud, that there are several security policies in place.

00:12:13.719 --> 00:12:18.119
So we do have to go through them to ensure that the services offered by

00:12:18.919 --> 00:12:24.039
any cloud service provider is blessed by our security team.

00:12:24.039 --> 00:12:26.840
That's how we work.

00:12:26.840 --> 00:12:31.719
Number two, I think there was a question was, yeah, right.

00:12:31.719 --> 00:12:34.760
So we run everything in AWS.

00:12:35.479 --> 00:12:36.039
We do.

00:12:36.039 --> 00:12:41.640
I don't want to call it a server hosting SaaS and R, because end of the day,

00:12:41.640 --> 00:12:44.840
from a tactical perspective, these are different assets.

00:12:44.840 --> 00:12:49.080
But it is a part of the same ecosystem, as I mentioned earlier.

00:12:49.080 --> 00:12:55.960
That is the statistical and program compute environment, which is a validated platform.

00:12:56.760 --> 00:13:00.919
Think of it as a platform consisting of multiple components.

00:13:00.919 --> 00:13:02.599
SaaS is one of them.

00:13:02.599 --> 00:13:03.559
R is another.

00:13:04.119 --> 00:13:06.200
100% validated at this time.

00:13:09.640 --> 00:13:12.119
I don't know, Rachel, if there was another question there.

00:13:12.119 --> 00:13:12.840
Was there another?

00:13:14.039 --> 00:13:16.039
No, I think that was great.

00:13:16.599 --> 00:13:21.239
And Bill, feel free to put in the chat if you wanted any more context on that, too.

00:13:21.239 --> 00:13:24.359
But I see, Eric, you just added a question to the chat, too.

00:13:24.359 --> 00:13:25.640
Do you want to jump in?

00:13:25.640 --> 00:13:26.119
Sure.

00:13:26.119 --> 00:13:28.280
It's great to virtually see you again, Satish.

00:13:28.280 --> 00:13:30.599
We've had some great conversations in the past.

00:13:30.599 --> 00:13:35.239
Really admire what your team is doing to push really novel uses of tech.

00:13:36.359 --> 00:13:40.840
I'd be curious if you could tell this group more about how containerization

00:13:41.559 --> 00:13:46.200
is helping play a role in your cloud deployments on AWS,

00:13:46.200 --> 00:13:50.359
and have you had any issues integrating those technologies together?

00:13:50.359 --> 00:13:56.440
And also, how are you getting your data science colleagues, your statistician colleagues,

00:13:56.440 --> 00:14:00.039
on board with using these platforms that depend on these services?

00:14:00.599 --> 00:14:01.880
If you could elaborate on that.

00:14:02.679 --> 00:14:03.239
Certainly.

00:14:04.039 --> 00:14:10.039
So I mentioned AWS, but one of the key components of this is containerization,

00:14:10.039 --> 00:14:11.719
Eric, as you rightfully pointed out.

00:14:11.719 --> 00:14:15.479
Yeah, I was hoping that somebody would ask that question.

00:14:16.119 --> 00:14:23.400
So everything in a validated environment, because the need or the ask is to ensure

00:14:23.400 --> 00:14:30.119
repeatability and reproducibility, the only logical choice at this time is containers.

00:14:30.359 --> 00:14:31.799
We try to containerize.

00:14:33.000 --> 00:14:33.960
Well, we have to.

00:14:33.960 --> 00:14:35.080
It's not that we need to.

00:14:35.080 --> 00:14:36.440
We have to containerize.

00:14:37.159 --> 00:14:42.039
So the space platform, I have a responsibility for the R part of it.

00:14:42.039 --> 00:14:44.440
So I'm going to concentrate a little bit more there.

00:14:45.080 --> 00:14:50.280
So one, users would want to basically run through their studies using R.

00:14:50.280 --> 00:14:52.200
And how do we do it is the question.

00:14:52.200 --> 00:14:57.880
So we are using the POSIT Workbench as our launch pad.

00:14:58.599 --> 00:15:02.440
This is deployed on a traditional EC2 instance.

00:15:02.440 --> 00:15:07.960
And then, you know, either we run ad hoc just to ensure for the users.

00:15:08.679 --> 00:15:13.479
This is a, first of all, this is a production platform, but there is a logical grouping

00:15:13.479 --> 00:15:18.119
where our users would first want to come and test it in a development area

00:15:18.119 --> 00:15:21.880
and then move it into the traditional QA and prod.

00:15:21.880 --> 00:15:26.840
But the way they would first test in the development area is number one,

00:15:27.799 --> 00:15:31.479
the entire RStudio POSIT Workbench is containerized.

00:15:31.479 --> 00:15:36.440
So we always ensure that we try to keep up with the latest release of POSIT.

00:15:36.440 --> 00:15:39.239
I think we are just one release behind at this time.

00:15:39.799 --> 00:15:42.760
And there are some unique challenges around it.

00:15:42.760 --> 00:15:47.000
The challenges are mostly about the IQ, OQ, and the time that it takes.

00:15:47.000 --> 00:15:49.640
For example, it's not just POSIT.

00:15:49.640 --> 00:15:53.000
There are other vendors who are helping us with this effort.

00:15:53.960 --> 00:15:58.840
We have to go through a formal process of vetting, validating, and verifying.

00:15:58.840 --> 00:16:00.359
So all of this takes time.

00:16:00.359 --> 00:16:02.280
So typically, we lag behind.

00:16:02.280 --> 00:16:04.039
That's one challenge that we have.

00:16:04.760 --> 00:16:07.320
Number two, because we have containerized,

00:16:07.320 --> 00:16:13.239
it gives our users the capability to test something that is locked on

00:16:13.239 --> 00:16:17.080
and be ensured that, you know, again, from a repeatability perspective,

00:16:17.719 --> 00:16:20.599
containers are the only way that will help them with that.

00:16:20.599 --> 00:16:24.520
So first, we will go through defining the process

00:16:24.520 --> 00:16:28.919
and specifying the requirements as to what really needs to go into the container.

00:16:28.919 --> 00:16:35.479
For example, if our users have identified a set of workflows that they would want

00:16:36.359 --> 00:16:40.119
for, you know, to help them with the clinical studies that they are looking into.

00:16:40.919 --> 00:16:45.640
Traditionally, it will map to a set of, you know, if I have to wear a tactical hat,

00:16:45.640 --> 00:16:49.559
it is eventually going to boil down to R packages.

00:16:49.559 --> 00:16:53.080
The R packages that need to make it into this container.

00:16:53.080 --> 00:16:57.159
So this is where we pretty much are using standard technologies

00:16:57.159 --> 00:16:59.159
and tools that are used in the industry.

00:16:59.159 --> 00:17:00.919
We have a Jenkins pipeline.

00:17:01.479 --> 00:17:06.760
We are using the POSIX Workbench to, sorry, the package manager to lock down

00:17:07.479 --> 00:17:12.839
versions of R packages that we would want to go into the container.

00:17:12.839 --> 00:17:17.959
So we, and there are some, you know, business processes that are defined

00:17:17.959 --> 00:17:23.239
as to what will, what should go into this container in terms of R packages.

00:17:23.239 --> 00:17:28.599
Once we have defined, we run through the build process to create the container

00:17:29.160 --> 00:17:34.439
and we will verify it in the traditional Studio Workbench.

00:17:35.319 --> 00:17:39.719
Once, you know, our users are comfortable that, yes, this is the workflow,

00:17:39.719 --> 00:17:44.599
this fits our model and we don't see any issues, that container is then blocked

00:17:44.599 --> 00:17:47.640
and then it moves into the QA slash prod area.

00:17:47.640 --> 00:17:51.079
And that's where they would run through the,

00:17:52.119 --> 00:17:55.560
and that is what is deemed as a validated run.

00:17:55.560 --> 00:18:00.680
Anything that the users would try out in their development environment

00:18:00.680 --> 00:18:04.439
is a prerequisite, but it is not deemed as a validated run.

00:18:04.439 --> 00:18:09.479
It is only when it is run through the production that it is deemed as validated.

00:18:09.479 --> 00:18:14.520
In order to do that, not all of these validated runs behind the scenes

00:18:14.520 --> 00:18:19.479
will run as a service account user, because we want to ensure that number one,

00:18:19.479 --> 00:18:23.800
no particular user runs it in their environment and it runs in a service account.

00:18:24.359 --> 00:18:28.680
Behind the scenes, we also have the traditional EKS cluster

00:18:29.959 --> 00:18:33.800
and where we scale up and launch these containers.

00:18:34.760 --> 00:18:35.959
Thank you, Satish.

00:18:37.400 --> 00:18:42.119
I was just going to say in the chat, I am definitely still learning all the AWS acronyms too.

00:18:43.560 --> 00:18:47.719
So, if anybody wants to share those in the chat too, that's really helpful.

00:18:48.520 --> 00:18:51.959
One part of the question earlier that we had missed,

00:18:52.920 --> 00:18:55.239
and I think would be really helpful to cover as well is,

00:18:55.959 --> 00:19:01.880
what role does a partner like a Taurus play in facilitating the AWS?

00:19:02.119 --> 00:19:06.359
Okay, we pretty much rely on a Taurus.

00:19:06.359 --> 00:19:10.680
We are partnering with the Taurus mainly for the validation aspect of it,

00:19:12.280 --> 00:19:19.479
Rachel, and what I mean by that is, all of the R packages that we want to qualify,

00:19:20.119 --> 00:19:27.479
a Taurus is helping us with writing the IQ, OQs that need to run.

00:19:27.640 --> 00:19:32.280
For example, when we build the container, yes, we have a list of R packages,

00:19:32.920 --> 00:19:37.319
but how do we ensure that they fit the user's requirements?

00:19:37.880 --> 00:19:43.239
So, one advantage, one unique thing that we have done inside this is,

00:19:44.920 --> 00:19:49.160
we do joint collaboration when we build the container

00:19:49.160 --> 00:19:54.839
and we run through the automatic process of running through the IQ, OQs,

00:19:55.079 --> 00:20:01.640
process of running through the IQ, OQ steps that has been written by the Taurus team.

00:20:02.199 --> 00:20:06.920
The advantage is, once you go through the container build process,

00:20:06.920 --> 00:20:10.760
one, we are, as I mentioned earlier, we are verifying,

00:20:10.760 --> 00:20:13.959
saying that these are the list of R packages that get installed,

00:20:13.959 --> 00:20:19.079
but at the same time, the scripts will run during the build process,

00:20:19.079 --> 00:20:23.239
which runs through these IQ, OQ steps, and at the end of the day,

00:20:23.560 --> 00:20:26.359
it will generate a validation report

00:20:26.359 --> 00:20:31.239
where we go through each and every IQ step that has been written.

00:20:31.239 --> 00:20:34.599
It could be install package A, then, you know,

00:20:34.599 --> 00:20:39.880
ensure that all of the functionality within that package fits our requirements,

00:20:39.880 --> 00:20:42.839
and this is where the OQ part of it helps.

00:20:44.599 --> 00:20:47.079
So, we run through the build process,

00:20:47.079 --> 00:20:50.040
and then at the end of the day, we inspect the validation report.

00:20:50.040 --> 00:20:53.959
Then we take a look, hey, did all of the test cases pass?

00:20:54.599 --> 00:20:56.760
If it failed, what was the reason?

00:20:56.760 --> 00:21:00.119
Is this because of an underlying system dependency,

00:21:00.119 --> 00:21:04.920
or is this because some other additional package that we forgot needs to be,

00:21:04.920 --> 00:21:09.959
so, you know, installed, or is it simply because there was a bug somewhere?

00:21:09.959 --> 00:21:11.479
And we go through this process.

00:21:11.479 --> 00:21:13.319
It's an iterative process.

00:21:13.319 --> 00:21:18.199
This is where Taurus is basically building the entire IQ, OQ part of it

00:21:18.199 --> 00:21:20.920
and taking responsibility for the validation aspect.

00:21:22.920 --> 00:21:23.880
That's great. Thank you.

00:21:24.920 --> 00:21:28.599
And I don't know if somebody from Taurus want to chime in as well.

00:21:28.599 --> 00:21:30.520
I did want to give them the opportunity

00:21:30.520 --> 00:21:32.280
because they are the ones who are writing this.

00:21:34.520 --> 00:21:38.680
Yeah, I would just say it was Satish working with you from the beginning,

00:21:38.680 --> 00:21:41.239
getting that design of the entire pipeline worked out

00:21:41.239 --> 00:21:43.479
so that it could all fit within the container build.

00:21:43.479 --> 00:21:46.359
I mean, that being an upfront requirement of what you wanted to see there,

00:21:47.000 --> 00:21:50.760
but it's been a close relationship with Satish and the business unit

00:21:50.760 --> 00:21:54.359
to make sure that we can get the right boxes checked

00:21:54.359 --> 00:21:55.640
for everything that they want to do.

00:21:56.359 --> 00:21:59.800
But we've gotten this nice fully automated pipeline

00:21:59.800 --> 00:22:03.719
that's proved fairly resilient when we've gone through updates of everything

00:22:03.719 --> 00:22:07.400
as we continue to expand and improve the environment.

00:22:07.400 --> 00:22:11.079
And this has been a combination of some of the internally developed packages

00:22:11.959 --> 00:22:14.040
within the Janssen team,

00:22:14.040 --> 00:22:16.839
focusing on some of their environmental workflows

00:22:17.560 --> 00:22:21.560
as well as the other packages that are in use within the environment.

00:22:21.560 --> 00:22:23.640
So there's been a lot of different components of this

00:22:23.640 --> 00:22:29.239
that have come together to make this focus product

00:22:29.239 --> 00:22:32.599
for the team to deploy within their space environment.

00:22:34.520 --> 00:22:35.079
Thanks, Mike.

00:22:37.479 --> 00:22:39.719
I want to jump over to some of the Slido questions too

00:22:39.719 --> 00:22:42.599
to make sure we get to some of those anonymous ones over there.

00:22:42.599 --> 00:22:43.880
And one from earlier was,

00:22:44.760 --> 00:22:48.920
Satish, as data scientists and statisticians request support

00:22:48.920 --> 00:22:52.760
for open source tools that are new to their organization,

00:22:52.760 --> 00:22:54.119
how do you think about this?

00:22:55.160 --> 00:22:59.079
So thinking through tech debt or other issues,

00:22:59.800 --> 00:23:03.079
they're trying to understand your IT's perspective

00:23:04.359 --> 00:23:05.800
from the requests that you receive.

00:23:06.920 --> 00:23:08.040
So, yes.

00:23:08.040 --> 00:23:11.640
So, one, there is a fairly easy part of it.

00:23:11.640 --> 00:23:14.119
That is, what do you need this for?

00:23:14.119 --> 00:23:15.079
Why do you need it?

00:23:15.079 --> 00:23:16.760
And that's a simpler question,

00:23:16.760 --> 00:23:21.239
because there will always be a convincing argument from the users

00:23:21.239 --> 00:23:24.439
where they'll say, I need it to solve this particular problem.

00:23:25.400 --> 00:23:28.760
However, the other part of it is, as I mentioned earlier,

00:23:28.760 --> 00:23:31.160
we do have to go through a security process

00:23:31.160 --> 00:23:35.880
where some of this build process that I mentioned earlier,

00:23:35.880 --> 00:23:38.680
where we go through it behind the scenes,

00:23:38.680 --> 00:23:41.000
they come in and scan the container

00:23:41.000 --> 00:23:44.359
where they trigger a security validation report

00:23:44.359 --> 00:23:46.040
to check for vulnerabilities.

00:23:47.160 --> 00:23:48.520
And then they will flag it.

00:23:48.520 --> 00:23:51.400
If it's a showstopper, we have to address it.

00:23:52.040 --> 00:23:52.839
No questions asked.

00:23:52.839 --> 00:23:53.959
We have to address it.

00:23:53.959 --> 00:23:57.079
It could be a simple question of installing a newer version

00:23:57.079 --> 00:23:58.760
of the system dependency.

00:23:59.319 --> 00:24:01.479
And if our validation fails at that reason,

00:24:01.479 --> 00:24:04.040
then we will somehow have to ensure

00:24:04.040 --> 00:24:05.479
that all the checks and balances,

00:24:06.520 --> 00:24:08.359
basically we pass all the checks.

00:24:08.359 --> 00:24:10.839
So when a request for a new tool comes in,

00:24:10.839 --> 00:24:14.920
we also have to check with our internal security team

00:24:15.479 --> 00:24:19.160
to see if they have any concerns.

00:24:20.520 --> 00:24:22.599
Most of the times, yeah, it's okay.

00:24:22.599 --> 00:24:24.839
But sometimes they will alert us saying,

00:24:24.839 --> 00:24:28.920
hey, do you know that there is a vulnerability risk with it?

00:24:28.920 --> 00:24:31.400
Here is the reason why we are going to stop this.

00:24:31.959 --> 00:24:36.119
Most often, they will also suggest a workaround

00:24:36.119 --> 00:24:39.479
or to see how we can address that.

00:24:39.479 --> 00:24:42.520
But when a request for a new tool comes in

00:24:42.520 --> 00:24:44.680
or when a new R package comes in,

00:24:44.680 --> 00:24:47.239
we have to go through the security checks

00:24:48.280 --> 00:24:51.719
just to ensure that we don't expose ourselves

00:24:51.719 --> 00:24:54.040
for any vulnerability.

00:24:54.040 --> 00:24:55.160
Yes, it is true.

00:24:55.160 --> 00:24:57.400
Things are sitting behind a firewall.

00:24:57.400 --> 00:24:58.199
Yes, it is true.

00:24:58.199 --> 00:25:00.599
They are all running inside a container

00:25:00.599 --> 00:25:02.680
where the chances are a lot less

00:25:02.680 --> 00:25:07.400
than when it runs in a traditional data center.

00:25:07.959 --> 00:25:10.439
But we do have to ensure that we comply

00:25:10.439 --> 00:25:14.119
with all of the security risks and challenges.

00:25:15.800 --> 00:25:17.640
Thank you very much.

00:25:18.599 --> 00:25:21.959
I see, Alan, you had asked the question in the chat too.

00:25:21.959 --> 00:25:23.000
Do you want to jump in next?

00:25:25.560 --> 00:25:26.060
Sure.

00:25:26.599 --> 00:25:27.640
Yeah, hi, Satish.

00:25:27.640 --> 00:25:28.439
This is really interesting.

00:25:28.839 --> 00:25:30.680
I haven't been working with our clinical team

00:25:30.680 --> 00:25:31.400
for a number of years,

00:25:31.400 --> 00:25:33.160
so I'm a little bit distant

00:25:33.160 --> 00:25:36.119
from the state of the art of that operation.

00:25:36.839 --> 00:25:39.959
But a lot of my experience at the time

00:25:39.959 --> 00:25:42.359
had to do with just having credibility

00:25:42.359 --> 00:25:44.839
with our SQA and regulatory teams

00:25:47.560 --> 00:25:52.359
for credibility to work them through a comfort level

00:25:52.359 --> 00:25:53.959
with supporting what we were doing.

00:25:54.599 --> 00:25:56.599
And I wonder if you could speak a little bit to

00:25:57.239 --> 00:25:59.640
what did that take between the IT team,

00:25:59.640 --> 00:26:02.040
the clinical team, the users

00:26:02.040 --> 00:26:05.160
to bring them along to these new tools and platforms.

00:26:05.160 --> 00:26:06.439
I've got to think that there was a lot

00:26:06.439 --> 00:26:07.800
of change management there.

00:26:07.800 --> 00:26:10.359
And I'm wondering if there were any sort of critical things

00:26:10.359 --> 00:26:12.040
that made the difference for you

00:26:12.040 --> 00:26:15.719
to get regulatory on board with saying,

00:26:15.719 --> 00:26:17.160
okay, we're comfortable speaking

00:26:17.160 --> 00:26:20.040
to these systems in an audit, for example.

00:26:21.479 --> 00:26:24.520
So let me see how I can.

00:26:25.479 --> 00:26:26.520
There's a lot there, yeah.

00:26:26.520 --> 00:26:28.119
Any parts of it would be great.

00:26:28.119 --> 00:26:30.280
Yeah, so you mentioned users

00:26:30.280 --> 00:26:31.640
and I also mentioned,

00:26:31.640 --> 00:26:34.439
I think you mentioned regulatory agencies as well.

00:26:35.319 --> 00:26:36.520
As far as regulate

00:26:36.520 --> 00:26:39.319
and then our internal validation team,

00:26:39.319 --> 00:26:40.760
TQ team, all of that.

00:26:40.760 --> 00:26:42.439
Let me see if I can address that

00:26:42.439 --> 00:26:44.040
in bits and pieces of that.

00:26:44.040 --> 00:26:46.760
One, the users, they were on board with that

00:26:46.760 --> 00:26:48.760
because number one, as I said,

00:26:48.760 --> 00:26:50.119
they would also want to learn

00:26:50.119 --> 00:26:51.880
from others' experience as well.

00:26:52.520 --> 00:26:55.079
Mike mentioned the internally developed R packages.

00:26:55.079 --> 00:26:56.680
So they are also contributing

00:26:56.680 --> 00:26:59.079
to the open source as well at this time.

00:26:59.079 --> 00:27:03.959
So there's both give and take, learn from each other.

00:27:03.959 --> 00:27:06.680
So for the users, it was pretty easy

00:27:06.680 --> 00:27:08.359
and they were the ones who were saying,

00:27:08.359 --> 00:27:11.959
hey, we want this because this is going to help us

00:27:12.760 --> 00:27:15.000
get to where we want simply

00:27:15.000 --> 00:27:16.839
because of the open source contribution.

00:27:16.839 --> 00:27:20.920
And because things were much faster when it came to R.

00:27:22.280 --> 00:27:26.119
When it came to where the TQ team,

00:27:26.119 --> 00:27:28.439
our internal quality team, right?

00:27:28.439 --> 00:27:32.199
Number one, they wanted to ensure one,

00:27:32.199 --> 00:27:35.719
we were basically putting a check mark

00:27:35.719 --> 00:27:37.560
against everything that they asked for.

00:27:38.119 --> 00:27:39.640
This was new for them.

00:27:39.640 --> 00:27:41.000
We had to sit with them.

00:27:41.000 --> 00:27:43.239
For example, the Docker build process

00:27:43.239 --> 00:27:46.839
that I mentioned earlier, they had several questions.

00:27:46.839 --> 00:27:50.119
We had to prove it to them that no matter what,

00:27:50.119 --> 00:27:52.359
what I run today, if I have to come back

00:27:52.359 --> 00:27:53.800
and run it again tomorrow,

00:27:53.800 --> 00:27:56.119
except for the timestamp that it was built,

00:27:56.680 --> 00:27:58.119
we had to show and prove

00:27:58.119 --> 00:28:00.439
that it was going through the same process.

00:28:00.439 --> 00:28:02.599
No matter how many times we re-build,

00:28:02.599 --> 00:28:05.079
we were going to get the exact same result.

00:28:05.079 --> 00:28:07.319
Yes, there will be some challenges along the way.

00:28:07.319 --> 00:28:10.599
It wasn't easy because we were also new to it,

00:28:10.599 --> 00:28:13.079
but we were able to prove it to them.

00:28:13.079 --> 00:28:16.199
And it required many, I want to say weeks,

00:28:16.199 --> 00:28:18.199
months of effort trying to convince them

00:28:18.199 --> 00:28:21.640
because again, sometimes when you are in the vanguard,

00:28:21.640 --> 00:28:26.680
the onus is on you to prove that what you are doing

00:28:26.680 --> 00:28:28.920
is not violating any norms,

00:28:28.920 --> 00:28:31.160
well-established norms and practices.

00:28:31.160 --> 00:28:32.359
So it took us some time.

00:28:33.880 --> 00:28:37.479
So once they were convinced that the tools

00:28:37.479 --> 00:28:39.880
and technologies that we had used

00:28:39.880 --> 00:28:41.560
conformed to their requirements,

00:28:41.560 --> 00:28:43.239
they gave their seal of approval.

00:28:43.239 --> 00:28:45.319
Of course, they were also learning in this process

00:28:45.319 --> 00:28:47.800
because again, with cloud technology,

00:28:47.800 --> 00:28:49.560
sometimes they'll ask questions like,

00:28:49.560 --> 00:28:51.560
hey, what is your failback mechanism?

00:28:52.119 --> 00:28:53.959
What happens if things go down?

00:28:53.959 --> 00:28:56.839
And then, as I mentioned earlier, we are all on AWS.

00:28:56.839 --> 00:29:00.439
So we had to tell them we have the power of AWS.

00:29:00.439 --> 00:29:02.839
We wouldn't want to worry about something going down

00:29:02.839 --> 00:29:03.880
or having catastrophic,

00:29:03.880 --> 00:29:05.640
but yet we had to plan for it.

00:29:06.280 --> 00:29:07.479
We had to plan for it.

00:29:09.079 --> 00:29:13.160
And then even something as simple as disaster and recovery,

00:29:13.160 --> 00:29:14.439
how do you recover from that?

00:29:15.079 --> 00:29:16.119
It's not like you could go

00:29:16.119 --> 00:29:19.239
and build something immediately in another data center

00:29:19.239 --> 00:29:24.040
because we are locked down to a particular AWS region,

00:29:24.040 --> 00:29:26.680
which is U.S. Northeast one

00:29:26.680 --> 00:29:30.119
that is extremely popular for most of the folks out here,

00:29:30.119 --> 00:29:32.760
U.S. East one, Northern Virginia region.

00:29:32.760 --> 00:29:36.119
So we had to basically convince them that,

00:29:36.119 --> 00:29:38.520
yes, there are some well-founded fears,

00:29:38.520 --> 00:29:42.199
but no, we don't have to be totally paranoid about that.

00:29:42.920 --> 00:29:45.880
The question about the health regulatory

00:29:45.880 --> 00:29:48.680
agencies and how did we convince them?

