and comfortable with EKS,

00:32:50.760 --> 00:32:53.640
Carpenter to help us with autoscaling,

00:32:53.640 --> 00:32:56.280
that is something that we are evaluating at this time.

00:32:57.319 --> 00:32:59.640
Again, as I said, everything has to be blessed

00:32:59.640 --> 00:33:01.160
from our security team

00:33:01.160 --> 00:33:03.560
and from our internal compliance team as well.

00:33:04.280 --> 00:33:07.160
Because even if we have to implement

00:33:07.160 --> 00:33:11.880
what might be regarded as a small change on the platform,

00:33:11.880 --> 00:33:16.119
because these are what I consider validated platforms,

00:33:16.119 --> 00:33:19.479
there is extensive scrutiny that we are subjected to,

00:33:19.479 --> 00:33:22.040
mainly in terms of documentation.

00:33:22.040 --> 00:33:25.560
Sometimes it takes a little longer than we would want.

00:33:25.560 --> 00:33:27.800
For example, we could deploy things

00:33:27.800 --> 00:33:29.319
in our development environment

00:33:29.319 --> 00:33:31.000
where it's pretty much open.

00:33:31.000 --> 00:33:34.119
We can go and evaluate whatever we want implemented there

00:33:34.119 --> 00:33:35.560
and then we will find out,

00:33:35.560 --> 00:33:37.880
oh my gosh, it took us only two minutes to do this,

00:33:37.880 --> 00:33:40.520
but it is going to take a couple of hours

00:33:40.520 --> 00:33:43.000
simply because we have to provide proof

00:33:43.000 --> 00:33:45.079
at each and every step

00:33:45.079 --> 00:33:47.719
so that if we have to replicate this at a later time,

00:33:47.719 --> 00:33:50.760
we have all of those protocols in place.

00:33:51.319 --> 00:33:54.359
So yeah, it will take a little bit longer to get there,

00:33:54.359 --> 00:33:57.319
but that is one challenge that we have today.

00:34:00.680 --> 00:34:01.180
Thank you.

00:34:02.119 --> 00:34:03.719
One of the SIDO questions,

00:34:03.719 --> 00:34:06.760
and I know we touched a bit already on the collaboration

00:34:06.760 --> 00:34:08.199
that happens between teams,

00:34:08.199 --> 00:34:10.280
especially with security,

00:34:10.840 --> 00:34:13.479
but do you have any tips about working internally

00:34:13.479 --> 00:34:15.479
with your peers and leadership

00:34:15.479 --> 00:34:17.800
to invest in moving towards new platforms?

00:34:20.760 --> 00:34:21.260
Yes.

00:34:23.399 --> 00:34:27.560
One of the things that we have to be cognizant of

00:34:27.560 --> 00:34:30.439
is the cost aspect of it, right?

00:34:30.439 --> 00:34:34.520
See, when we do things in the cloud environment,

00:34:34.520 --> 00:34:37.879
we absolutely need to have our leadership support.

00:34:38.840 --> 00:34:43.320
That is because with in-house data centers,

00:34:43.320 --> 00:34:44.760
with in-house equipment,

00:34:44.760 --> 00:34:47.479
there is a finite cost that is associated with it,

00:34:47.479 --> 00:34:49.959
whether it is the initial capital cost

00:34:49.959 --> 00:34:51.479
or the maintenance cost of it,

00:34:51.479 --> 00:34:54.040
we know what it is and we can always project that.

00:34:54.760 --> 00:34:56.600
The challenge with AWS

00:34:56.600 --> 00:34:59.239
or with any of the cloud service providers,

00:34:59.239 --> 00:35:00.840
I want to say cloud provider,

00:35:00.840 --> 00:35:03.639
is you cannot predict those charges up front

00:35:03.639 --> 00:35:08.439
because we generally tend to pay after the fact.

00:35:08.439 --> 00:35:11.080
So I could, for example,

00:35:11.080 --> 00:35:12.840
the load testing that we talked about earlier,

00:35:12.840 --> 00:35:16.439
how much can we go and how much loads can we test?

00:35:17.239 --> 00:35:18.840
If we have to start testing,

00:35:18.840 --> 00:35:21.320
then we will automatically start scaling up.

00:35:21.320 --> 00:35:22.760
We won't realize it.

00:35:22.760 --> 00:35:24.840
And then at the end of the month,

00:35:24.840 --> 00:35:26.600
when we are handed the bill,

00:35:26.600 --> 00:35:29.239
like, what, did I incur so much of cost?

00:35:29.239 --> 00:35:31.560
They will tell us here is the reason why.

00:35:31.560 --> 00:35:33.159
That is a unique challenge.

00:35:33.159 --> 00:35:35.080
But on the other side of it,

00:35:35.080 --> 00:35:37.959
consider post-COVID world

00:35:37.959 --> 00:35:39.719
where we were completely shielded

00:35:39.719 --> 00:35:43.000
because none of us ever came to a JNJ location.

00:35:43.000 --> 00:35:44.679
We were pretty much remote.

00:35:44.679 --> 00:35:46.280
We were 100% functional

00:35:46.280 --> 00:35:49.959
and all of that was because we were in the cloud.

00:35:49.959 --> 00:35:52.520
So there are certain benefits as well.

00:35:52.520 --> 00:35:53.959
The cost part of it,

00:35:53.959 --> 00:35:55.879
you have to have management support.

00:35:55.879 --> 00:35:58.120
The huge advantage with that is now,

00:35:58.840 --> 00:36:00.360
hey, something happened

00:36:00.360 --> 00:36:04.040
with the instance in your data center.

00:36:04.040 --> 00:36:06.199
Somebody has to go and physically verify

00:36:06.199 --> 00:36:07.879
whether it is pulling out a hard disk,

00:36:07.879 --> 00:36:09.080
replacing it.

00:36:09.080 --> 00:36:10.840
All of that would cost subsequent,

00:36:11.639 --> 00:36:12.760
substantial billers.

00:36:13.320 --> 00:36:15.399
With any of the cloud providers,

00:36:15.399 --> 00:36:16.679
you don't have that challenge.

00:36:16.679 --> 00:36:18.040
Something happened, you stop that,

00:36:18.040 --> 00:36:19.080
you start it back up

00:36:19.080 --> 00:36:21.320
because they give you all the tools

00:36:21.320 --> 00:36:23.639
to be back up and running in no time.

00:36:26.360 --> 00:36:28.360
So I see there's a conversation

00:36:28.360 --> 00:36:30.280
happening in the chat here

00:36:30.280 --> 00:36:31.479
and I can't really read it,

00:36:31.479 --> 00:36:33.879
but I know it started off Mike's question.

00:36:33.879 --> 00:36:36.600
So Mike, I'd love to have you ask that too.

00:36:39.080 --> 00:36:40.760
Thanks, Satish, thanks.

00:36:42.360 --> 00:36:44.280
It's nice to hear about another big pharma company

00:36:44.280 --> 00:36:47.879
using containers and the qualification process.

00:36:47.879 --> 00:36:49.879
I've been at the sharp end of that for many years.

00:36:51.399 --> 00:36:53.639
And from my perspective,

00:36:53.639 --> 00:36:55.800
it's fantastic to be able to qualify at once

00:36:56.439 --> 00:36:57.639
and then deploy it,

00:36:57.639 --> 00:36:59.800
use it in many, many places.

00:36:59.800 --> 00:37:01.800
It's one of the big strengths of this approach.

00:37:01.800 --> 00:37:03.399
But how do you balance up

00:37:03.399 --> 00:37:05.879
the kind of slow and steady approach

00:37:06.600 --> 00:37:09.080
of qualification, deployment,

00:37:09.639 --> 00:37:12.199
keeping things nice and documented

00:37:12.199 --> 00:37:14.040
and nice and steady

00:37:14.840 --> 00:37:18.520
versus colleagues who want latest, greatest,

00:37:18.520 --> 00:37:19.399
give me it tomorrow,

00:37:19.399 --> 00:37:20.760
I've got an urgent deadline.

00:37:21.320 --> 00:37:27.080
Yeah, so let me talk about it

00:37:27.080 --> 00:37:29.239
from a validated platform perspective

00:37:29.239 --> 00:37:31.239
because I think that it's relevant.

00:37:31.239 --> 00:37:34.199
Yes, we do get asked that question.

00:37:34.199 --> 00:37:37.639
For example, for one of the more recent studies,

00:37:37.639 --> 00:37:41.479
it did require us to install a new package

00:37:42.360 --> 00:37:44.919
which required some system dependencies.

00:37:45.479 --> 00:37:49.719
And there is no instantaneous answer.

00:37:51.159 --> 00:37:53.879
That's sadly, when you have to containerize,

00:37:53.879 --> 00:37:57.560
you have to balance your long-term prospects

00:37:57.560 --> 00:38:00.679
saying that yes, there is a short-term pain,

00:38:00.679 --> 00:38:03.080
but there is a long-term gain.

00:38:03.080 --> 00:38:05.719
And yes, it does frustrate our users sometimes

00:38:05.719 --> 00:38:09.239
because we will not be able to react to it

00:38:09.239 --> 00:38:10.280
simply because again,

00:38:10.280 --> 00:38:12.360
when you go through this build process,

00:38:12.360 --> 00:38:14.760
you will encounter challenges, trust me.

00:38:15.879 --> 00:38:20.439
But where I see a silver lining is,

00:38:20.439 --> 00:38:22.040
we have incredible partners,

00:38:22.040 --> 00:38:23.959
both from POSIT as well as Arturas

00:38:23.959 --> 00:38:25.959
who are helping Janssen with that approach.

00:38:26.679 --> 00:38:28.280
So anytime we have a challenge,

00:38:28.280 --> 00:38:32.600
for example, when we deployed our workbench,

00:38:33.399 --> 00:38:34.760
due to the nature of it,

00:38:34.760 --> 00:38:37.959
every organization will have their own unique challenges.

00:38:37.959 --> 00:38:40.679
I promise you that, every organization.

00:38:40.679 --> 00:38:43.080
One of the things that we had internally deployed

00:38:43.080 --> 00:38:45.320
was how we were treating our clinical data

00:38:45.320 --> 00:38:48.040
in terms of active directory groups,

00:38:48.040 --> 00:38:49.159
a little bit more tactical.

00:38:49.719 --> 00:38:53.560
But when we realized that the initial deployment

00:38:53.560 --> 00:38:55.399
of workbench did not work out,

00:38:55.399 --> 00:38:58.120
they were able to quickly come up with a release

00:38:58.120 --> 00:39:00.840
and then come up with an update saying,

00:39:00.840 --> 00:39:04.280
here is how we are going to help you get there.

00:39:04.280 --> 00:39:06.520
So we were able to deploy a new version.

00:39:06.520 --> 00:39:08.760
There, it wasn't a question of what,

00:39:08.760 --> 00:39:10.840
if it was a question of when we wanted

00:39:10.840 --> 00:39:15.879
and we were able to adapt that quickly, fairly quickly.

00:39:15.879 --> 00:39:18.679
But then the process that it takes to get there,

00:39:19.159 --> 00:39:21.159
documenting each and everything,

00:39:21.719 --> 00:39:23.320
that there is no shortcut.

00:39:23.320 --> 00:39:25.879
I'm afraid there's absolutely no shortcut

00:39:25.879 --> 00:39:28.840
because our TQ team wants proof that,

00:39:28.840 --> 00:39:31.879
hey, show us evidence that what you did.

00:39:31.879 --> 00:39:35.479
So there's extensive IQOQ that we go through as well.

00:39:36.919 --> 00:39:39.719
Yeah, there is absolutely no shortcut,

00:39:39.719 --> 00:39:43.560
but we always have to tell what is right,

00:39:43.560 --> 00:39:45.800
do the right thing as everybody says,

00:39:45.800 --> 00:39:47.879
saying that, yes, there is a short-term pain,

00:39:47.879 --> 00:39:49.879
but there is a long-term gain there.

00:39:51.320 --> 00:39:54.199
I would also just add that there's a completely separate

00:39:54.199 --> 00:39:56.919
like business unit consideration for this as well,

00:39:56.919 --> 00:39:58.679
because Mike, with you at Pfizer,

00:39:58.679 --> 00:40:00.199
you're also another group that has

00:40:00.199 --> 00:40:02.520
like a large group of SAS users.

00:40:02.520 --> 00:40:05.879
And the target group that this is going out to in Janssen

00:40:05.879 --> 00:40:07.479
is that SAS business unit.

00:40:07.479 --> 00:40:10.199
So Satish is just one part of this,

00:40:10.199 --> 00:40:12.760
our adoption effort that goes into the packages

00:40:12.760 --> 00:40:15.479
that are tidy TLG was just released open source,

00:40:15.479 --> 00:40:17.080
but that was designed to be able to support

00:40:17.080 --> 00:40:20.120
Janssen standards to be able to live up to all of that

00:40:20.120 --> 00:40:20.840
within that group.

00:40:20.840 --> 00:40:23.800
But then you have all of these business users

00:40:23.800 --> 00:40:25.080
who have gone through SAS training

00:40:25.719 --> 00:40:27.479
to get on board with that.

00:40:27.479 --> 00:40:29.560
And if you start changing everything under foot

00:40:29.560 --> 00:40:32.439
without bringing them along with you too quickly,

00:40:33.000 --> 00:40:36.199
then that will also upset the business users

00:40:36.919 --> 00:40:38.120
in a different way.

00:40:38.120 --> 00:40:39.959
So there's definitely a balance to strike

00:40:39.959 --> 00:40:43.239
that you need to consider from an organizational standpoint.

00:40:44.360 --> 00:40:45.159
Yeah, I see one.

00:40:45.159 --> 00:40:46.679
Sorry, go ahead.

00:40:46.679 --> 00:40:49.800
I think the kind of folks involved

00:40:49.800 --> 00:40:51.479
in reporting clinical trials data

00:40:52.360 --> 00:40:55.719
want it to be nice, controlled, well-managed,

00:40:55.719 --> 00:40:57.719
slow-changing, predictable.

00:40:59.000 --> 00:41:00.600
You know, it's other groups

00:41:02.199 --> 00:41:03.639
who have more rapid turnaround

00:41:05.000 --> 00:41:08.120
and the statisticians in some senses

00:41:08.120 --> 00:41:09.719
and supporting those groups

00:41:09.719 --> 00:41:11.320
that want the kind of latest, greatest.

00:41:12.199 --> 00:41:13.879
You know, this has just emerged on CRAN.

00:41:13.879 --> 00:41:15.639
Now I want it because it solves my problem.

00:41:17.000 --> 00:41:19.800
But I think, you know, like Satish is saying it,

00:41:19.800 --> 00:41:23.560
that the process to just simply fold that

00:41:23.560 --> 00:41:25.320
into the existing framework

00:41:25.320 --> 00:41:27.399
is not as simple as many people think.

00:41:28.280 --> 00:41:29.479
So I'm agreeing.

00:41:30.360 --> 00:41:32.280
Yeah, it never is.

00:41:32.280 --> 00:41:35.399
It will take some time to get us there.

00:41:35.399 --> 00:41:39.560
But the one thing that the users absolutely want

00:41:39.560 --> 00:41:40.919
is stability.

00:41:40.919 --> 00:41:43.959
We don't want to introduce changes

00:41:43.959 --> 00:41:46.280
which will potentially break things.

00:41:47.479 --> 00:41:48.840
So that's a red flag.

00:41:48.840 --> 00:41:49.639
That's a no-no.

00:41:49.639 --> 00:41:53.080
And this is where we spend careful amount of time,

00:41:53.080 --> 00:41:54.840
you know, substantial amount of time

00:41:54.840 --> 00:41:56.840
ensuring that care is given

00:41:56.840 --> 00:41:59.159
to ensuring backward compatibility.

00:41:59.159 --> 00:42:00.919
We don't break things.

00:42:00.919 --> 00:42:02.600
And this all, at the end of the day,

00:42:02.600 --> 00:42:06.360
will depend on how much of IQ-OQ

00:42:06.360 --> 00:42:08.199
you are willing to go through,

00:42:08.199 --> 00:42:10.840
how much of effort you are going to put into it.

00:42:12.439 --> 00:42:13.800
And I think it is well worth it.

00:42:14.040 --> 00:42:16.439
I'm getting the feeling that this is a topic

00:42:16.439 --> 00:42:18.280
that we definitely want to stay on.

00:42:18.280 --> 00:42:20.520
And there's a lot of thoughts on here too.

00:42:21.879 --> 00:42:24.919
I see, Eric, I think you added in,

00:42:24.919 --> 00:42:27.080
you said you had something to comment on here too.

00:42:27.080 --> 00:42:27.879
Do you want to jump in?

00:42:30.360 --> 00:42:31.879
Yeah, I had a few of them.

00:42:31.879 --> 00:42:35.879
But I think the key points that I was commenting on

00:42:35.879 --> 00:42:38.360
are that containerization,

00:42:38.360 --> 00:42:41.879
we're looking at this from kind of the broader level

00:42:42.679 --> 00:42:45.719
for an organization's analytical platform.

00:42:46.280 --> 00:42:47.479
I'm interested, Satish,

00:42:47.479 --> 00:42:50.120
if you've been keeping an eye on things

00:42:50.120 --> 00:42:52.199
like GitHub Codespaces,

00:42:52.199 --> 00:42:55.239
where it's giving, you know, at a repository level,

00:42:55.239 --> 00:42:57.959
the ability to containerize its environment.

00:42:58.679 --> 00:42:59.560
I mean, you can do that

00:42:59.560 --> 00:43:01.879
without GitHub Codespaces as well, I suppose.

00:43:01.879 --> 00:43:04.199
But I'm just curious where you find,

00:43:04.199 --> 00:43:10.199
where your opinion is on maybe those other analysts

00:43:10.840 --> 00:43:13.479
or statisticians that want to be on the cutting edge

00:43:13.479 --> 00:43:14.760
for a particular project,

00:43:14.760 --> 00:43:17.080
and they try to take matters in their own hands

00:43:17.080 --> 00:43:18.840
if they have a little know-how container,

00:43:18.840 --> 00:43:21.320
how containers work with Docker and the like,

00:43:21.320 --> 00:43:23.239
compared to what you're trying to do

00:43:23.239 --> 00:43:25.080
from this, you know, more broader effort,

00:43:25.080 --> 00:43:26.840
which is obviously hugely valuable too.

00:43:28.199 --> 00:43:32.360
Yeah, one thing that I must have forgotten to mention

00:43:32.360 --> 00:43:36.840
is even with the containers that internally get deployed,

00:43:36.840 --> 00:43:39.879
our technology services team will tell us,

00:43:40.600 --> 00:43:44.439
you know, what we could use as a base, right?

00:43:44.439 --> 00:43:46.280
In other words, we just cannot go

00:43:46.280 --> 00:43:48.199
and pull anything from Docker Hub.

00:43:48.199 --> 00:43:50.199
It has to be validated again

00:43:50.199 --> 00:43:52.120
because they want to do a scan of it.

00:43:52.120 --> 00:43:54.919
So there are some, I want to say,

00:43:56.600 --> 00:43:57.800
well-defined requirements.

00:43:57.800 --> 00:43:59.320
I don't want to call it constraints.

00:43:59.320 --> 00:44:02.280
It could be as simple as you have to use

00:44:02.280 --> 00:44:04.600
this version of CentOS 7 container.

00:44:04.600 --> 00:44:06.360
I'm just throwing out as an example.

00:44:07.080 --> 00:44:09.239
We can't simply go and use Ubuntu

00:44:09.239 --> 00:44:13.639
unless it is supported inside our J&J ecosystem.

00:44:13.639 --> 00:44:15.639
There is, you know, I'm sure folks are familiar

00:44:15.639 --> 00:44:16.840
with artifactory.

00:44:16.840 --> 00:44:18.919
Artifactory is where, you know,

00:44:18.919 --> 00:44:21.080
we host our container images

00:44:21.080 --> 00:44:25.000
and where we also pull certain base images as well.

00:44:25.000 --> 00:44:27.560
So to answer your question, Eric,

00:44:27.560 --> 00:44:30.760
we cannot go and pull directly from GitHub,

00:44:30.760 --> 00:44:33.080
but to answer a second part of it is,

00:44:33.080 --> 00:44:34.040
say for example,

00:44:34.679 --> 00:44:36.840
if you were to point me to some GitHub repo,

00:44:36.840 --> 00:44:37.959
can you support this?

00:44:37.959 --> 00:44:39.800
The short answer is maybe.

00:44:39.800 --> 00:44:41.399
And the reason I said maybe is

00:44:41.399 --> 00:44:43.560
we can go and take a look into it,

00:44:43.560 --> 00:44:46.439
see what software modules are being installed

00:44:46.439 --> 00:44:49.399
as a part of it in the container,

00:44:49.399 --> 00:44:53.000
see what it is that we could immediately use,

00:44:53.000 --> 00:44:56.120
or if it requires some sort of a substitution

00:44:56.120 --> 00:44:59.159
by say, for example, some other equivalent package,

00:44:59.159 --> 00:45:01.479
then we will go and download it, install it.

00:45:01.479 --> 00:45:03.959
All of that, so long as it is blessed

00:45:03.959 --> 00:45:05.800
by our technology services team,

00:45:05.800 --> 00:45:07.320
we will be able to do it.

00:45:07.320 --> 00:45:11.080
So the same challenge exists for our users as well.

00:45:11.959 --> 00:45:14.040
They have to rely on somebody in IT

00:45:14.040 --> 00:45:15.479
to help build them that.

00:45:15.479 --> 00:45:18.679
Yes, we are deploying pipelines, for example,

00:45:18.679 --> 00:45:22.280
might refer to the internally developed R package as well.

00:45:23.560 --> 00:45:26.439
We are now establishing pipelines

00:45:26.439 --> 00:45:29.479
where users from the business partners

00:45:29.479 --> 00:45:32.199
that we work with can develop an R package.

00:45:33.000 --> 00:45:35.320
And by simply doing the cut and paste

00:45:35.320 --> 00:45:38.199
of the basic necessities of the pipeline,

00:45:38.199 --> 00:45:39.800
we use Jenkins pipeline.

00:45:39.800 --> 00:45:41.959
We call it Jenkins Pipeline Manager.

00:45:41.959 --> 00:45:44.919
So they'll take that part of the infrastructure code,

00:45:44.919 --> 00:45:47.479
replicate it, and then work on

00:45:47.479 --> 00:45:49.479
what they are best qualified to do.

00:45:49.479 --> 00:45:51.320
That is work on the R package

00:45:51.320 --> 00:45:54.040
and not have to worry about the mundane aspects of,

00:45:54.040 --> 00:45:55.159
oh, how do I build it?

00:45:55.159 --> 00:45:56.280
How do I link it?

00:45:56.280 --> 00:45:58.439
Because all of that is streamlined to a point

00:45:58.520 --> 00:46:00.040
where we run through the linting,

00:46:00.040 --> 00:46:01.479
unit testing process,

00:46:01.479 --> 00:46:03.959
all of it when an R package is being built.

00:46:03.959 --> 00:46:07.800
So we help them by deploying those pipelines as well.

00:46:07.800 --> 00:46:12.199
So we make it sort of easier on them,

00:46:12.199 --> 00:46:16.520
but sometimes I might be trivializing things.

00:46:16.520 --> 00:46:19.719
Some users might find it a little bit more challenging

00:46:20.919 --> 00:46:21.959
for their test,

00:46:21.959 --> 00:46:23.800
but we are trying to templatize it

00:46:24.919 --> 00:46:27.239
to minimize disruption to the users.

00:46:28.520 --> 00:46:31.399
How to minimize learnings for our users

00:46:32.439 --> 00:46:33.959
because that's infrastructure, right?

00:46:33.959 --> 00:46:36.600
I mean, they might be focused more

00:46:36.600 --> 00:46:38.919
on clinical trial reporting efforts

00:46:38.919 --> 00:46:41.000
than have to worry about mundane activities

00:46:41.000 --> 00:46:42.439
like, oh, how do I build this?

00:46:42.439 --> 00:46:43.399
Because that's IT.

00:46:46.679 --> 00:46:47.879
Yeah, that's very helpful.

00:46:47.879 --> 00:46:50.439
And I consider myself one of maybe four or five people

00:46:50.439 --> 00:46:51.800
in my entire organization

00:46:51.800 --> 00:46:54.199
that likes both sides of that spectrum,

00:46:54.199 --> 00:46:56.280
but we can't expect all the sessions

00:46:56.280 --> 00:46:58.120
to be as geeky about this as people like me.

00:46:59.159 --> 00:46:59.659
Yeah.

00:47:00.679 --> 00:47:02.840
Nick, I see you had a great comment

00:47:02.840 --> 00:47:05.959
on building the adoption

00:47:05.959 --> 00:47:08.280
and I'd love to spend a few minutes

00:47:08.280 --> 00:47:10.120
talking about that too if you want to jump in.

00:47:12.520 --> 00:47:14.360
Sure, is there a specific question?

00:47:15.879 --> 00:47:18.040
Well, no, I just saw you were talking about

00:47:18.040 --> 00:47:22.439
like educating the users about validation as well.

00:47:23.719 --> 00:47:24.439
Right, yeah, yeah.

00:47:24.439 --> 00:47:26.840
This goes back to Mike's question around,

00:47:27.000 --> 00:47:28.840
how do you deal with validated

00:47:28.840 --> 00:47:30.600
versus like having the latest greatest?

00:47:30.600 --> 00:47:32.120
So yeah, I just threw in my two cents.

00:47:32.120 --> 00:47:35.399
I think the big part from our side is really education.

00:47:35.399 --> 00:47:39.000
So I guess Eric kind of mentioned as well,

00:47:39.000 --> 00:47:40.679
a lot of the users don't really care,

00:47:40.679 --> 00:47:43.239
but you have to sort of help them understand

00:47:43.239 --> 00:47:44.520
this is difficult, right?

00:47:44.520 --> 00:47:46.520
It's not just, I want this, let's have it.

00:47:47.320 --> 00:47:50.600
We have to consider accuracy, reproducibility,

00:47:50.600 --> 00:47:52.199
traceability of these things.

00:47:52.199 --> 00:47:54.600
Of most important is that our results are correct

00:47:54.600 --> 00:47:56.439
and they understand that, right?

00:47:56.520 --> 00:47:59.000
So that's kind of what we used to make sure like,

00:47:59.000 --> 00:48:00.919
okay, we have to validate this.

00:48:00.919 --> 00:48:02.120
Here's what it takes to do it.

00:48:02.120 --> 00:48:03.479
It's a significant effort.

00:48:04.760 --> 00:48:05.800
So that takes a little time,

00:48:05.800 --> 00:48:07.800
but then really use case driven.

00:48:07.800 --> 00:48:09.560
So sometimes people ask for things

00:48:09.560 --> 00:48:10.520
just because they want them.

00:48:10.520 --> 00:48:11.239
But then when you say, well,

00:48:11.239 --> 00:48:12.280
what do you want to use it for?

00:48:12.840 --> 00:48:14.120
You start getting more details

00:48:14.120 --> 00:48:15.320
that they don't really need it.

00:48:15.320 --> 00:48:18.360
So having that use case driven validation,

00:48:18.360 --> 00:48:19.320
what do you need it for?

00:48:19.320 --> 00:48:19.959
Why do you need it?

00:48:20.600 --> 00:48:22.040
Is it for production or is it something

00:48:22.040 --> 00:48:24.919
you could just use as like an exploratory environment, right?

00:48:24.919 --> 00:48:26.520
Do we really have to validate this?

00:48:27.159 --> 00:48:29.479
And that really shortens the list a lot more.

00:48:29.479 --> 00:48:32.520
And then once we get to, okay, we get it, you need it.

00:48:33.479 --> 00:48:35.639
We don't have the expertise as like the team

00:48:35.639 --> 00:48:37.239
that's overseeing it.

00:48:37.239 --> 00:48:39.560
You're now sort of our de facto expert on this.

00:48:40.360 --> 00:48:42.360
Put some skin in the game, help us out with this.

00:48:43.719 --> 00:48:45.560
And then sometimes they're willing to do it

00:48:45.560 --> 00:48:47.000
versus maybe they say,

00:48:47.000 --> 00:48:50.120
well, I see you've already validated the stats package

00:48:50.120 --> 00:48:51.080
is approved for use.

00:48:51.080 --> 00:48:52.760
I could do the stats package instead.

00:48:52.760 --> 00:48:54.040
Let me just use that, you know,

00:48:54.040 --> 00:48:56.439
and it sort of helps again, shorten that list down.

00:48:56.439 --> 00:48:56.939
So.

00:48:58.199 --> 00:48:58.840
Thank you.

00:48:58.840 --> 00:49:00.040
It's really helpful.

00:49:00.040 --> 00:49:00.540
Sure thing.

00:49:02.199 --> 00:49:05.399
Travis, I realized I had missed a question of yours earlier

00:49:05.399 --> 00:49:08.120
and I wanted to have you jump in next with your question.

00:49:09.719 --> 00:49:11.879
Did I ask a question that wasn't answered?

00:49:11.879 --> 00:49:12.600
I think you did.

00:49:14.360 --> 00:49:16.679
So I could, it was earlier when I missed it,

00:49:16.679 --> 00:49:19.000
but it was about, are there any open source

00:49:20.360 --> 00:49:22.840
IQ, OQ pipelines for R?

00:49:23.399 --> 00:49:24.520
Oh yeah, yeah, yeah.

00:49:24.520 --> 00:49:27.080
Mike had some good commentary in the chat around that too.

00:49:27.959 --> 00:49:30.040
Yeah, because I mean, I guess sort of the source

00:49:30.040 --> 00:49:33.320
of my question was for many use cases

00:49:33.320 --> 00:49:35.239
and clinical research like we're doing,

00:49:36.120 --> 00:49:41.239
it would seem that the IQ, OQ need not be overly complicated

00:49:41.239 --> 00:49:43.000
because if we just want to ensure

00:49:43.000 --> 00:49:45.000
that R was properly installed and can run

00:49:46.040 --> 00:49:49.239
dplyr, dbplyr pipelines can run a regression

00:49:49.239 --> 00:49:51.239
and a time to event analysis without trouble.

00:49:51.239 --> 00:49:52.600
We're not doing anything fancy.

00:49:53.159 --> 00:49:55.719
It would seem, couldn't I just do some minimal set of checks

00:49:57.560 --> 00:50:00.919
for which someone might write a reasonable starting point

00:50:01.560 --> 00:50:03.959
in the open source realm for like,

00:50:03.959 --> 00:50:05.800
has R actually properly installed?

00:50:05.800 --> 00:50:08.360
And does it actually do these three, four packages

00:50:08.360 --> 00:50:09.959
do the thing that they're supposed to do?

00:50:11.239 --> 00:50:13.639
Just curious about like what a minimum viable product

00:50:13.639 --> 00:50:14.600
for that might look like.

00:50:14.600 --> 00:50:17.479
But this is, of course, a Taurus's realm of expertise.

00:50:17.479 --> 00:50:19.800
So I really don't know what those answers would look like.

00:50:21.639 --> 00:50:24.439
Yeah, and just to note, one of the things

00:50:24.439 --> 00:50:27.080
that we've really taken the guidance from

00:50:27.080 --> 00:50:29.239
is the work that was done in the R validation hub

00:50:29.239 --> 00:50:32.120
to start defining what a risk-based approach

00:50:32.120 --> 00:50:33.560
to validation is around that.

00:50:33.560 --> 00:50:37.879
So for, and for things like a lot of the base R stuff,

00:50:37.879 --> 00:50:41.560
a lot of the tidyverse maintained packages,

00:50:42.919 --> 00:50:46.439
those are, Nick, what is the term that we landed on?

00:50:46.439 --> 00:50:50.520
Accepted for that where you can run the package unit tests

00:50:50.520 --> 00:50:51.639
and you can accept that.

00:50:52.280 --> 00:50:54.520
But again, part of this is also documenting the evidence

00:50:54.520 --> 00:50:56.760
that that was done so that you can pass those through.

00:50:58.199 --> 00:51:00.760
Satish's team get the report so that we can log that

00:51:00.760 --> 00:51:03.560
into the QA systems so that you have the evidence

00:51:03.560 --> 00:51:05.159
and traceability that that was done.

00:51:06.199 --> 00:51:09.080
But then like Nick says, when you get into other things

00:51:09.080 --> 00:51:11.080
and especially getting into the more statistical realm

00:51:11.080 --> 00:51:13.560
of things, having use case driven approaches

00:51:13.560 --> 00:51:14.760
around what you're looking for,

00:51:15.399 --> 00:51:17.560
how you can defend the integrity of that.

00:51:18.199 --> 00:51:20.360
And then let my comment back to you was,

00:51:21.000 --> 00:51:22.760
you're saying that it works, what does work mean?

00:51:23.719 --> 00:51:25.800
What is the kind of baseline

00:51:25.800 --> 00:51:27.479
that you're assessing that against?

00:51:27.479 --> 00:51:29.560
So there's a lot of kind of questions

00:51:29.560 --> 00:51:32.040
that you need to go in and investigate and answer that

00:51:32.040 --> 00:51:34.439
so that you're defending yourself

00:51:34.439 --> 00:51:37.159
because all of this comes back to what happens

00:51:37.159 --> 00:51:38.679
if you have to undergo an audit.

00:51:38.679 --> 00:51:40.679
What if a regulatory agency comes back to you

00:51:41.320 --> 00:51:42.600
and then start testing the questions

00:51:42.600 --> 00:51:45.159
of how you're verifying what you're doing?

00:51:46.360 --> 00:51:49.800
So that's the worst case scenario

00:51:49.800 --> 00:51:51.000
and something like this would be

00:51:51.959 --> 00:51:55.239
that something is turned around

00:51:55.239 --> 00:51:59.719
because of the integrity of your system was questioned.

00:51:59.719 --> 00:52:02.040
And pharma, I think that a lot of times

00:52:03.719 --> 00:52:05.639
pharma is extremely risk averse

00:52:05.639 --> 00:52:07.000
just because of the investment

00:52:07.000 --> 00:52:08.760
that goes into getting where things are.

00:52:08.760 --> 00:52:11.399
Statistical programming is an extremely small window

00:52:11.399 --> 00:52:13.479
in the larger scope of everything that's going on.

00:52:14.120 --> 00:52:16.199
And no one wants to be the person

00:52:16.199 --> 00:52:19.080
who kind of is a showstopper for something

00:52:19.080 --> 00:52:21.399
or even delays can just be extremely costly.

00:52:22.679 --> 00:52:29.479
But yeah, we're working in extremely risk averse industry.

00:52:30.199 --> 00:52:31.560
That's a fascinating answer

00:52:31.560 --> 00:52:33.719
especially regarding the unit tests for that.

00:52:33.719 --> 00:52:35.159
I mean, it hadn't occurred to me

00:52:35.159 --> 00:52:38.600
but it's probably a good message to developers

00:52:38.600 --> 00:52:39.719
like write good unit tests

00:52:39.719 --> 00:52:42.520
and then there's actually almost unintended

00:52:42.520 --> 00:52:44.600
but fortunate downstream consequences

00:52:44.600 --> 00:52:46.760
of writing good unit tests.

00:52:46.760 --> 00:52:48.360
So you could just write out that report

00:52:48.439 --> 00:52:50.520
like for example, the tidyverse unit tests

00:52:50.520 --> 00:52:52.360
which I know are comprehensive and good.

00:52:53.399 --> 00:52:54.600
Check out, that's awesome.

00:52:56.040 --> 00:52:57.159
Yeah, and one of the things

00:52:57.159 --> 00:52:59.479
that at least our technology services team

00:52:59.479 --> 00:53:02.439
is pushing for is to ensure

00:53:02.439 --> 00:53:06.760
that every R package goes through some static analysis

00:53:06.760 --> 00:53:09.479
saying, okay, here's what's being deployed.

00:53:10.600 --> 00:53:13.639
Is this like, did it go through all the checks and balances?

00:53:13.639 --> 00:53:14.919
Sometimes it's impossible

00:53:14.919 --> 00:53:16.679
and sometimes it's not possible.

00:53:17.320 --> 00:53:19.080
And it depends on who you're talking to.

00:53:19.080 --> 00:53:22.919
For the users, does it work for my particular use case?

00:53:22.919 --> 00:53:24.439
Go deploy the package.

00:53:24.439 --> 00:53:25.800
Somebody else comes in later

00:53:25.800 --> 00:53:28.280
and finds out that it's causing a conflict.

00:53:28.280 --> 00:53:30.280
That's a red flag.

00:53:31.080 --> 00:53:34.280
Sometimes security might only be looking at it

00:53:34.280 --> 00:53:36.040
from a slightly different perspective.

00:53:36.040 --> 00:53:37.800
They don't care about the functionality.

00:53:38.600 --> 00:53:40.919
They care about the security aspect of it.

00:53:40.919 --> 00:53:43.879
So if it passes all the vulnerabilities checks

00:53:43.879 --> 00:53:46.439
then you are good to go from their perspective.

00:53:47.320 --> 00:53:50.439
But I go back to this comment that you had earlier,

00:53:50.439 --> 00:53:52.679
Travis, that, you know, hey, I just installed it.

00:53:52.679 --> 00:53:53.399
Did it work?

00:53:53.399 --> 00:53:54.760
I'm gonna go and use it.

00:53:55.399 --> 00:53:57.639
There is a danger as Mike pointed out.

00:53:57.639 --> 00:54:00.679
I've personally seen one effort at least.

00:54:01.320 --> 00:54:02.280
I don't want to say fail

00:54:02.280 --> 00:54:04.760
but it has reached a point where nobody wants to use this

00:54:04.760 --> 00:54:06.360
because, you know, IT took this approach

00:54:06.360 --> 00:54:07.959
that, yeah, we're gonna build this.

00:54:07.959 --> 00:54:09.719
Then I do a minimal qualification

00:54:09.719 --> 00:54:11.719
for us if it installed R, good.

00:54:11.719 --> 00:54:12.760
It passed our check.

00:54:13.479 --> 00:54:15.639
Then they said it's on the users

00:54:15.719 --> 00:54:18.520
like Nick and others to go install the R packages

00:54:19.159 --> 00:54:19.959
for what they want.

00:54:19.959 --> 00:54:22.439
And then they suddenly realized that, you know,

00:54:22.439 --> 00:54:25.080
as everybody knows in the R ecosystem

00:54:25.080 --> 00:54:27.479
most of the packages are users can install.

00:54:27.479 --> 00:54:30.199
There is this small subset that is sometimes, you know

00:54:30.199 --> 00:54:32.760
it requires a unique dependency, which is easy

00:54:32.760 --> 00:54:36.280
but sometimes it does require things to be handled.

00:54:36.280 --> 00:54:37.719
And that's where the users say,

00:54:37.719 --> 00:54:40.600
I don't have these expertise and I'm sorry

00:54:40.600 --> 00:54:41.959
I just cannot use this.

00:54:41.959 --> 00:54:43.959
So there is a danger to it

00:54:43.959 --> 00:54:46.600
when you do minimum qualification.

00:54:46.600 --> 00:54:48.679
I for one certainly don't believe in it

00:54:48.679 --> 00:54:49.879
and wouldn't encourage that.

00:54:50.600 --> 00:54:52.840
We have to take our users workflow

00:54:52.840 --> 00:54:56.439
ensure that everything is tested accurately.

00:54:56.439 --> 00:54:59.000
As Mike pointed out, it's just to make sure

00:54:59.000 --> 00:55:00.600
that we defend ourselves.

00:55:00.600 --> 00:55:02.199
God forbid if there is an audit

00:55:02.199 --> 00:55:03.719
and we have to show evidence

00:55:03.719 --> 00:55:05.479
of what we ran a couple of years ago.

00:55:06.520 --> 00:55:09.399
Trust me, that short-term pain

00:55:10.199 --> 00:55:11.879
leading to long-term gain.

00:55:11.879 --> 00:55:14.760
It's accurate in this place.

00:55:17.639 --> 00:55:18.679
Thank you Satish.

00:55:18.679 --> 00:55:19.879
I know we have a few minutes

00:55:19.879 --> 00:55:21.159
until the top of the hour here.

00:55:21.879 --> 00:55:25.399
Walter, I see you had asked a question a few minutes ago.

00:55:25.399 --> 00:55:26.679
Do you want to jump in and ask that?

00:55:32.280 --> 00:55:33.639
And there you are.

00:55:33.639 --> 00:55:34.439
Yep, I can hear you.

00:55:35.080 --> 00:55:35.719
Great.

00:55:35.719 --> 00:55:37.479
No, I was just curious because

00:55:38.360 --> 00:55:41.959
I understand that the versioning

00:55:41.959 --> 00:55:44.120
and the environment and everything

00:55:44.120 --> 00:55:48.600
for like say critical packages

00:55:48.600 --> 00:55:51.399
or critical tests that are maybe developed

00:55:51.399 --> 00:55:55.159
and deployed packages need to be in place.

00:55:55.159 --> 00:55:57.320
But I'm working in the finance industry.

00:55:57.320 --> 00:55:59.800
And so we also have artifactory in place

00:55:59.800 --> 00:56:04.679
for let's say less critical like convenience packages.

00:56:04.679 --> 00:56:06.520
And I just wanted to ask

00:56:06.760 --> 00:56:10.760
if they are mixing these using artifactory

00:56:10.760 --> 00:56:12.679
maybe as a package mirror,

00:56:12.679 --> 00:56:18.439
internal package mirror for less critical packages.

00:56:18.439 --> 00:56:21.239
So like user convenience stuff

00:56:21.239 --> 00:56:24.600
and these things or if they keep everything

00:56:24.600 --> 00:56:27.320
on the positive package manager.

00:56:27.320 --> 00:56:29.399
Just out of curiosity because you mentioned

00:56:29.959 --> 00:56:31.560
them having artifactory,

00:56:31.560 --> 00:56:33.479
having Jenkins pipelines in place

00:56:33.479 --> 00:56:34.439
and things like that.

00:56:35.159 --> 00:56:35.659
Thanks.

00:56:37.560 --> 00:56:39.560
So we will not distinguish

00:56:39.560 --> 00:56:42.919
whether a particular package is less important

00:56:42.919 --> 00:56:45.000
or one is more important, Walter.

00:56:45.000 --> 00:56:46.439
We just don't take that approach.

00:56:46.439 --> 00:56:49.320
If a user wants a package,

00:56:49.320 --> 00:56:53.479
we just go through the entire process of IQing, OQing.

00:56:53.479 --> 00:56:55.719
Yes, it will be in positive package manager.

00:56:55.719 --> 00:56:57.159
Yes, we will snapshot it.

00:56:57.159 --> 00:57:00.679
We will use the exact same snapshot to replicate it.

00:57:00.679 --> 00:57:03.560
But no, we do not say,

00:57:03.560 --> 00:57:05.080
hey, these are less important.

00:57:05.080 --> 00:57:07.800
This is going to not go through any qualification

00:57:07.800 --> 00:57:09.239
or any such thing like that.

00:57:09.239 --> 00:57:11.959
We just go through the totality of it.

00:57:13.399 --> 00:57:15.159
And as Nick pointed out earlier,

00:57:15.159 --> 00:57:16.439
the question will always be,

00:57:16.439 --> 00:57:17.879
why do you need this package?

00:57:17.879 --> 00:57:19.800
And once that question is answered

00:57:19.800 --> 00:57:21.159
from an IT perspective,

00:57:21.959 --> 00:57:23.239
it really doesn't matter

00:57:23.239 --> 00:57:25.000
towards the importance of that package.

00:57:27.000 --> 00:57:28.840
Yeah, but I was just curious,

00:57:30.280 --> 00:57:33.000
as I said, sometimes it makes sense

00:57:33.000 --> 00:57:35.479
to put the full force behind it.

00:57:35.479 --> 00:57:38.679
But sometimes if it's just like some reporting

00:57:38.679 --> 00:57:40.679
or some small, shiny dashboard

00:57:40.679 --> 00:57:42.840
that you want to share with colleagues internally,

00:57:42.840 --> 00:57:46.199
you know, they probably may be overkill

00:57:46.199 --> 00:57:48.600
to have it go through all the whole process.

00:57:48.600 --> 00:57:51.479
I was just curious if you had this approach as well,

00:57:51.479 --> 00:57:53.800
because where I come from, we have it.

00:57:53.800 --> 00:57:55.159
That's why I was just curious.

00:57:55.159 --> 00:57:55.800
Yeah, thanks.

00:57:57.560 --> 00:58:00.120
Now, it would be a little bit hard

00:58:00.120 --> 00:58:02.199
to treat it as a validated environment

00:58:02.199 --> 00:58:03.239
if we haven't gone through

00:58:03.239 --> 00:58:04.600
the checks and balance world.

00:58:07.959 --> 00:58:11.560
And one more question on packages too.

00:58:11.560 --> 00:58:14.199
I see, Javier, you had a question

00:58:15.239 --> 00:58:17.000
going back to the containers.

00:58:17.959 --> 00:58:18.919
Thanks, Rachel.

00:58:18.919 --> 00:58:20.199
Yeah, and I'm sorry.

00:58:20.199 --> 00:58:21.639
I've been in and out

00:58:22.439 --> 00:58:24.040
with side conversations with work.

00:58:24.040 --> 00:58:25.879
So my apologies if this was covered.

00:58:26.760 --> 00:58:28.520
But we have a similar setup

00:58:28.520 --> 00:58:33.159
where we build containers

00:58:33.159 --> 00:58:35.000
and have kind of snapshots

00:58:35.000 --> 00:58:38.600
of RStudio Package Manager.

00:58:38.600 --> 00:58:42.679
And as I guess one of the heavier users of R

00:58:43.719 --> 00:58:44.439
at the company,

00:58:45.959 --> 00:58:48.840
something that, you know, is not a big deal,

00:58:48.840 --> 00:58:50.600
just a weekly annoyance

00:58:50.600 --> 00:58:53.800
is that the versions of the packages

00:58:53.800 --> 00:58:56.040
that are loaded in these containers

00:58:56.040 --> 00:58:58.199
are, you know, specific versions

00:58:58.199 --> 00:59:00.760
that might have been snapped,

00:59:00.760 --> 00:59:02.040
let's say six months ago.

00:59:02.040 --> 00:59:07.000
So the first thing I do when I load my RStudio IDE,

00:59:07.000 --> 00:59:08.199
which is, you know, in the cloud,

00:59:09.320 --> 00:59:13.639
is to update the packages that are persisting.

00:59:13.639 --> 00:59:16.280
And then I install additional packages

00:59:17.000 --> 00:59:21.080
that, you know, I need for my workflow

00:59:21.080 --> 00:59:23.959
or Shiny app, et cetera.

00:59:23.959 --> 00:59:27.479
So I was just curious if, you know,

00:59:27.479 --> 00:59:31.159
you had, it'd be excellent

00:59:31.159 --> 00:59:35.399
if the package versions

00:59:35.399 --> 00:59:37.639
that were kind of booted

00:59:37.639 --> 00:59:39.320
when I loaded my RStudio

00:59:39.320 --> 00:59:41.320
would be the current versions

00:59:41.320 --> 00:59:43.479
of those packages deemed for persistence.

00:59:45.800 --> 00:59:46.919
And that's just something,

00:59:46.919 --> 00:59:48.360
I don't know that there's a better solution

00:59:48.360 --> 00:59:49.719
to what we have right now.

00:59:49.719 --> 00:59:52.280
I didn't know if there was, you know,

00:59:52.280 --> 00:59:53.639
maybe a recommendation you had.

00:59:54.919 --> 00:59:56.840
For a validated environment,

00:59:56.840 --> 00:59:57.959
the short answer is

00:59:57.959 --> 01:00:00.040
you just have to rebuild the container.

01:00:01.800 --> 01:00:04.919
And there's no other alternative.

01:00:06.199 --> 01:00:10.199
However, the process is,

01:00:11.239 --> 01:00:13.639
if you need new versions of existing packages,

01:00:13.639 --> 01:00:15.800
then, you know, you just go through

01:00:15.800 --> 01:00:17.320
the basic IQ OQ

01:00:17.320 --> 01:00:19.239
that was already written for that package.

01:00:19.239 --> 01:00:20.760
But if there's new functionality

01:00:20.760 --> 01:00:21.800
that you want to adopt,

01:00:21.800 --> 01:00:24.679
yes, you will have to write new IQ OQs,

01:00:24.679 --> 01:00:26.120
no questions asked.

01:00:26.120 --> 01:00:28.600
But there is no shortcut here.

01:00:28.600 --> 01:00:29.800
You just have to repeat

01:00:29.800 --> 01:00:31.800
and rinse through this entire process.

01:00:32.600 --> 01:00:33.479
Got it, okay.

01:00:33.479 --> 01:00:34.360
Thank you, I appreciate it.

01:00:35.080 --> 01:00:36.840
Sure, and we go through this, you know,

01:00:36.840 --> 01:00:37.800
whenever, you know,

01:00:37.800 --> 01:00:39.399
we have to build a new container

01:00:39.399 --> 01:00:41.000
from an IT perspective, right?

01:00:41.000 --> 01:00:43.080
We do check with users like Nick first.

01:00:43.080 --> 01:00:45.479
Hey, did it meet this, your requirement?

01:00:45.479 --> 01:00:47.000
And they have their own

01:00:47.000 --> 01:00:48.439
acceptance testing as well.

01:00:48.439 --> 01:00:50.199
Then he'll come back and say, nope,

01:00:50.199 --> 01:00:51.000
something failed.

01:00:51.000 --> 01:00:52.199
I need you to look into it.

01:00:52.199 --> 01:00:53.399
Yes, it's an, you know,

01:00:53.399 --> 01:00:56.439
basically it's a repeat and rinse, right?

01:00:56.439 --> 01:00:58.679
So you go through this process

01:00:58.679 --> 01:00:59.560
all over again.

01:00:59.560 --> 01:01:01.479
So go back to the drawing board,

01:01:01.479 --> 01:01:02.360
add the packaging,

01:01:02.360 --> 01:01:03.959
add any system dependencies,

01:01:03.959 --> 01:01:05.159
run through your IQ,

01:01:05.159 --> 01:01:07.800
you release the container for in development

01:01:07.800 --> 01:01:09.159
for, you know, users to test.

01:01:09.159 --> 01:01:11.239
And once they say, yep, this all looks good,

01:01:11.239 --> 01:01:12.600
it's at that time we,

01:01:12.600 --> 01:01:14.040
quote unquote, lock the container.

01:01:14.679 --> 01:01:18.199
I know we just passed the hour mark here

01:01:18.199 --> 01:01:20.360
and a few people had to jump off

01:01:20.360 --> 01:01:21.560
for other meetings.

01:01:21.560 --> 01:01:23.560
I just want to say thank you so much, Satish,

01:01:23.560 --> 01:01:26.280
for sharing your experience with us

01:01:26.280 --> 01:01:29.639
and also the Atorus team for joining.

01:01:29.639 --> 01:01:31.800
Satish, you are such a wealth of knowledge

01:01:32.520 --> 01:01:33.879
and it's been great getting to see

01:01:33.879 --> 01:01:35.959
more of the IT experience as well

01:01:35.959 --> 01:01:37.639
that we don't always get to talk about

01:01:37.639 --> 01:01:38.600
in these Hangouts.

01:01:38.600 --> 01:01:39.399
Thank you so much.

01:01:40.040 --> 01:01:41.000
My pleasure.

01:01:41.000 --> 01:01:42.439
Thank you for having me.

